<p><b>Frederick Winslow Taylor</b> (20 March 1856–21 March 1915), widely known as <b>F. W. Taylor</b>, was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> mechanical engineer who sought to improve <a href="/wiki/Industrial_efficiency" title="Industrial efficiency" class="mw-redirect">industrial efficiency</a>. He is regarded as the father of <a href="/wiki/Scientific_management" title="Scientific management">scientific management</a>, and was one of the first <a href="/wiki/Management_consulting" title="Management consulting">management consultants</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Taylor was one of the intellectual leaders of the <a href="/wiki/Efficiency_Movement" title="Efficiency Movement">Efficiency Movement</a> and his ideas, broadly conceived, were highly influential in the <a href="/wiki/Progressive_Era" title="Progressive Era">Progressive Era</a>.</p>
